The '''reveal''' (also known as the '''big reveal''') is a [[plot device]] in [[narrative structure]], and is the exposure to the reader or audience of a previously unseen key character or element of [[Plot (narrative)|plot]] or of the [[performance]].
A reveal is different from Aristotle's ''[[anagnorisis]]'', in which something is revealed to a character rather than to the audience.
==Narrative== The reveal may result in a [[plot twist]], and could be the key plot turn or unexpected [[Post-credits scene|coda]] in the story – in the [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] [[Literary genre|genre]], for example. It may also be used as a device (particularly in the [[Climax (narrative)|climax]]) in [[stage magic]] by an [[Magic (illusion)|illusionist]] or [[escape artist]].<ref name=Clark_2012>{{cite book |author=Clark, James L. |year=2012 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mekGtpHh5zUC&pg=PT159&dq=%22the+reveal%22+magic&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Qgz7T-bhF4uZiAfklsmABw&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22the%20reveal%22&f=false |chapter=Performing the Corkscrew |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd |title=Mind Magic and Mentalism for Dummies |accessdate=10 July 2012}}</ref>
== Stage magic == In a magician's act, "the reveal" may refer to<ref name=Clark_2012/> * the normal culmination of a trick * the unexpected (to the [[audience]]) culmination of the trick * an explanation of the trick – which itself may be immediately eclipsed by a version of the trick that the first reveal can't explain.
==Film== ''Reveal'' is also used for two distinct cinematographic techniques: * A slow, theatrically presented image of an important character or item not seen previously in the film; * A close-up, wide shot, or other unusual camera point-of-view that shows the audience an important visual clue not known to characters in the same scene.
In the sense of first-time showing of a character, a ''reveal'' is similar to, but usually not same as, the [[opening shot]] or [[Establishing shot]] that gives the location or context of a new scene.
