{{about|a popular phrase|Wikipedia's attitude towards lackadaisical ethos|WP:SEP}}
{{merge to|Diffusion of responsibility|discuss=Talk:Diffusion of responsibility#Proposed merge with Somebody else's problem|date=October 2018}} '''Somebody else's problem''' (also known as '''someone else's problem''' or '''SEP''') is a psychological effect{{Original research inline|date=November 2018}} where people choose to dissociate themselves from an issue that may be in critical need of recognition. Such issues may be of large concern to the population as a whole but can easily be a choice of ignorance by an individual.
Author [[Douglas Adams|Douglas Adams']] comedic description of the condition, which he ascribes to a physical "SEP field", has helped make it a generally recognized phenomenon.{{Original research inline|date=November 2018}} Somebody Else's Problem has been used to capture public attention on matters that may have been overlooked and has less commonly been used to identify concerns that an individual suffering symptoms of depression should ignore.{{Original research inline|date=November 2018}} This condition has also been employed as trivial shorthand to describe factors that are "out of scope" in the current context.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://meetings.informs.org/Conf/Miami2001//TALKS/Sponsor-25.html |title=INFORMS Miami 2001 Annual Meeting&nbsp;– TB18.2 Minisum Location with Closest Euclidean Distances |accessdate=2008-06-07}}</ref>{{not in source|date=November 2018}}
==Origin==
In [[Douglas Adams]]'s 1982 novel ''[[Life, the Universe and Everything]]'' (in ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy#Novels|The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]'' [[comedy science fiction]] series), the character [[Ford Prefect (character)|Ford Prefect]] says,
{{quote|An SEP is something we can't see, or don't see, or our brain doesn't let us see, because we think that it's somebody else's problem. That’s what SEP means. Somebody Else’s Problem. The brain just edits it out, it's like a blind spot.}}
The narration then explains:
{{quote|The Somebody Else's Problem field... relies on people's natural predisposition not to see anything they don't want to, weren't expecting, or can't explain. If Effrafax had painted the mountain pink and erected a cheap and simple Somebody Else’s Problem field on it, then people would have walked past the mountain, round it, even over it, and simply never have noticed that the thing was there.}}
==References by others==
Since the publication of {{H2G2|book|3|link=yes}}, the phrase has been used by others, such as:
* Referring to a team working on a [[computer programming]] project, [[Alan F. Blackwell]] once wrote: "Many sub-goals can be deferred to the degree that they become what is known amongst professional programmers as an 'S.E.P.'&nbsp;&ndash; somebody else's problem."<ref name=ppig-1997-01>{{Cite journal <!-- more info on this cite may someday show up at http://www.ppig.org/workshops/ppig-1997-9th-annual-workshop --> |url = http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~afb21/publications/PPIG97.html |title = Simulating a Software Project: The PoP Guns go to War |last1 = Blackwell |first1 = Alan F.|author-link= Alan F. Blackwell |last2 = Arnold |first2 = H.L. |journal = Proceedings of the 9th Annual Meeting of the Psychology of Programming Interest Group |pages = 53&ndash;60 |date = January 1997 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081026050403/http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~afb21/publications/PPIG97.html |archive-date = 2008-10-25 |dead-url = no |access-date = 2015-03-24 |quote = }}</ref>{{Original research inline|date=November 2018}} * Christopher Negus, writing on the origin of [[Unix]] at [[Bell Labs]] in the 1970s, described Bell Labs at the time as "a think tank where ideas came first and profits were somebody else's problem".<ref name=rhel4bib-2006>{{Cite book <!-- more cite info at https://www.amazon.com/Fedora-Red-Enterprise-Linux-Bible/dp/0471754919 --> |last = Negus |first = Christopher |title = Fedora 5 and Red Hat Enterprise Linux 4 Bible |chapter = Linux's roots in Unix (part 1, chapter 1, section 3) |publisher = Wiley |location = New York |via = [[TechTarget]] |series = Bible (Book 327) |date = 2006-05-10 |page = 6 |isbn = 978-0-4717-5491-6 <!--|isbn-10 = 0-471-75491-9 --> |oclc = 69746564 |chapter-url = http://searchitchannel.techtarget.com/feature/Linuxs-roots-in-Unix |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131213203844/http://searchitchannel.techtarget.com/feature/Linuxs-roots-in-Unix |archive-date = 2013-12-13 |dead-url = no |access-date = 2015-03-25 |quote = }}</ref>{{Original research inline|date=November 2018}} * Adams' description of an SEP field is quoted in an article of "psychological invisibility", where it is compared to other fictional effects such as the [[perception filter]] in ''[[Doctor Who]]'', as well as cognitive biases such as [[inattentional blindness]] and [[change blindness]].<ref>[http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/04/13/sight-unseen-critic-at-large-kathryn-schulz Sight unseen], Catherine Schulz, [[The New Yorker]], April 13, 2015</ref>
